    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 7, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💰 Anthropic Is Printing Money (And Spending It on Compute)\n\nThe AI company everyone's been calling \"the responsible one\" just revealed it's making $30 billion a year. Apparently responsibility pays.\n\n- **The revenue:** Anthropic's annualized run rate hit $30B — up from $9B at end of 2025. Enterprise customers spending $1M+ annually doubled to 1,000+ in under two months.\n- **The deal:** Google and Broadcom confirmed a 3.5-gigawatt TPU compute agreement to supply Anthropic's infrastructure buildout through 2027. That's not a server rack. That's a small power grid.\n\n*The company explicitly built to avoid catastrophic AI outcomes is now one of the fastest-growing enterprises in American history. No notes.*\n\n**Sources:** [The Register](https://www.theregister.com/2026/04/07/broadcom_google_chip_deal_anthropic_customer/) | [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-06/broadcom-confirms-deal-to-ship-google-tpu-chips-to-anthropic)\n\n---\n\n## 🥔 OpenAI's GPT-5.5 \"Spud\" Is Almost Ready. Maybe It's GPT-6. They Haven't Decided.\n\nOpenAI finished training a new frontier model three weeks ago and hasn't figured out what to call it yet.\n\n- **The model:** GPT-5.5, codenamed \"Spud,\" completed pretraining on March 24. CEO Sam Altman says release is \"a few weeks\" away. Co-founder Greg Brockman called it \"two years of research\" with a \"big model feel.\"\n- **The question:** OpenAI hasn't decided whether to market it as GPT-5.5 or GPT-6 depending on how the performance benchmarks land. DeepSeek V4 and Grok 5 are in the same release window. Q2 2026 is getting crowded.\n\n*The model is ready. The marketing is not. This is, somehow, the harder problem.*\n\n**Sources:** [PrimeAIcenter](https://primeaicenter.com/gpt-5-5-review/) | [Digital Applied](https://www.digitalapplied.com/blog/deepseek-v4-gpt-5-5-grok-5-ai-models-q2-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 📈 $239 Billion Went to AI Startups in Q1. That's 80% of All Global Venture Capital.\n\nVenture capitalists looked at every other sector in Q1 2026 and decided not today.\n\n- **The number:** Global VC hit $300B in Q1 2026 — a new all-time record — with AI capturing $239–242B of it. Four of the five largest venture rounds in history closed this quarter: OpenAI ($122B), Anthropic ($30B), xAI ($20B), Waymo ($16B).\n- **The context:** Q1 2026 foundational AI funding alone doubled everything raised in all of 2025. The remaining 20% of global VC was split between every other sector on Earth.\n\n*(Fine. Probably fine.)*\n\n**Sources:** [Crunchbase](https://news.crunchbase.com/venture/record-breaking-funding-ai-global-q1-2026/) | [Crunchbase](https://news.crunchbase.com/venture/foundational-ai-startup-funding-doubled-openai-anthropic-xai-q1-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Japan Is Spending $6.3 Billion on Robots Because It Has No Choice\n\nJapan committed ¥1 trillion to physical AI and robotics this week. The pitch: not automation anxiety — pure demographic math.\n\n- **The investment:** PM Takaichi's government announced $6.3B over five years for domestic physical AI. Target: 30% of the global physical AI market by 2040. Automated forklifts, warehouse systems, and facility inspection robots are moving to large-scale deployment.\n- **The argument:** Japan isn't replacing workers with robots. It's filling roles that have no workers. The country's labor shortage is structural and accelerating. Robots aren't the threat — they're the plan.\n\n*\"AI is coming for your job\" is a very American concern. Japan is asking whether there's an AI that would like to have one.*\n\n**Sources:** [Silicon Canals](https://siliconcanals.com/sc-n-japan-bets-6-3-billion-on-physical-ai-not-to-replace-workers-but-because-there-are-none-left-to-replace/) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/05/japan-is-proving-experimental-physical-ai-is-ready-for-the-real-world/)\n\n---\n\n## 👴 12,000 AI Robots Are Now Keeping Elderly South Koreans Company\n\nSouth Korea deployed 12,000+ AI companion robots into the homes of solitary elderly people. They run on ChatGPT. They might be doing more meaningful work than most enterprise AI.\n\n- **The deployment:** Hyodol robots monitor vitals, remind patients about medication, and alert social workers in emergencies. Korea faces a 1.55 million nursing staff shortage by 2032. Caregivers describe them as \"our eyes and ears between visits.\"\n- **The roadmap:** 2026 expansion includes telemedicine sites where Hyodols will analyze patient conversations for mental health deterioration. The robot has more patient context than most doctors.\n\n*An AI companion that monitors your health, alerts caregivers, and keeps you company. The bar for \"meaningful AI application\" just moved.*\n\n**Sources:** [Rest of World](https://restofworld.org/2025/korea-ai-robot-senior-care-hyodol/) | [AI Commission](https://aicommission.org/2026/04/ai-dolls-offer-companionship-to-the-elderly/)\n\n---\n\n## 💊 Utah Is Letting AI Renew Your Prescriptions. The FDA Is Watching.\n\nUtah became the first state to legally authorize autonomous AI prescription renewals, and the federal government is now paying close attention.\n\n- **The pilot:** Startup Doctronic launched a 12-month sandbox in January with authorization to autonomously renew 192 chronic-condition medications — excluding controlled substances. Physicians review AI outputs for the first 250 patients; complex cases escalate automatically.\n- **The concern:** The FDA is scrutinizing whether federal oversight is needed before other states follow suit. If Utah works, this becomes a template. If it doesn't, the same.\n\n*The question isn't whether AI can renew your blood pressure medication. The question is who's liable when it gets it wrong.*\n\n**Sources:** [Axios](https://www.axios.com/local/salt-lake-city/2026/01/07/utah-ai-drug-prescriptions-doctronic) | [MobiHealthNews](https://www.mobihealthnews.com/news/utah-allows-ai-renew-prescription-drugs-autonomously)"
